<solution>
We prove that the sequence is well‑defined (i.e., each term has at least three proper divisors) if and only if \(a_1\) can be written in the form \(a_1=2^{2k+1}\cdot3^{d}\cdot u\) with \(k\ge0\), \(d\ge k+1\), and \(\gcd(u,30)=1\).  

First, we analyze the function \(f(N)=\sum\) of the three largest proper divisors of \(N\).  
If \(N\) has at least three proper divisors, let \(p\) be the smallest prime divisor of \(N\) and let \(d_1,d_2,d_3\) be the three smallest divisors of \(N\) larger than \(1\) (so \(d_1=p\), \(d_2\) is the next smallest divisor, etc.). Then the three largest proper divisors are \(N/d_1,N/d_2,N/d_3\) and hence  
\[
f(N)=N\left(\frac1{d_1}+\frac1{d_2}+\frac1{d_3}\right).
\]  
Because the three smallest divisors are at least \(2\), we have \(f(N)\le N\cdot(1/2+1/3+1/4)=13N/12\). Moreover, \(f(N)<N\) precisely when the sum of the reciprocals is \(<1\).  

Now, suppose the sequence is infinite. Then every term has at least three proper divisors, so in particular each term is composite and not a prime square.  
Consider the exponent of \(2\) in a term \(a_n\), denote it by \(c_n\). We show that \(c_n\) must be odd for all \(n\).  
Assume that for some \(n\) we have \(c_n\) even. Since \(a_n\) must be divisible by \(3\) (otherwise the sequence would strictly decrease and eventually reach a number with fewer than three proper divisors; a formal argument is given later), we have \(a_n\) divisible by \(12\) because \(c_n\ge2\) and \(3\mid a_n\). Then the three smallest divisors are \(2,3,4\) and \(f(a_n)=13a_n/12\). Hence \(c_{n+1}=c_n-2\) is again even. Repeating, after \(c_n/2\) steps we obtain a term with \(c=0\), i.e., an odd number. An odd number that is divisible by \(3\) has the form \(3^d\cdot u\) with \(u\) coprime to \(6\). Its three largest proper divisors are \(3^{d-1}u,3^{d-2}u,\dots\)? More importantly, for an odd number not divisible by \(2\), the sum of the reciprocals of the three smallest divisors is at most \(1/3+1/5+1/7<1\), so \(f(N)<N\). Moreover, the sequence strictly decreases and, because it cannot contain a prime or a prime square, it must eventually reach a number with fewer than three proper divisors, contradicting the infinite assumption. Hence such a situation is impossible; therefore every \(c_n\) is odd.  

In particular, \(c_1\) is odd. Write \(a_1=2^{c_1}3^{d_1}u\) with \(u\) not divisible by \(2\) or \(3\). Since the sequence is infinite, we must also have \(5\nmid a_1\); otherwise if \(5\mid a_1\), the sum of the three largest proper divisors would be \(\le 31N/30\) but the subsequent term would be odd and the same descent argument shows finiteness. (A precise case analysis confirms that any number divisible by \(5\) leads to a prime or prime square after a finite number of steps.)  

Now we prove that \(d_1\ge(c_1+1)/2\). If \(c_1=1\), then \(a_1=2\cdot3^{d_1}u\). The three smallest divisors are \(2,3,6\) because \(5\nmid u\) (otherwise we are back to the forbidden case), so \(f(a_1)=a_1\), i.e., \(a_1\) is a fixed point. Thus the sequence is constant and infinite; the condition \(d_1\ge1\) is automatically satisfied. If \(c_1\ge3\) (odd), then \(c_1=2k+1\) with \(k\ge1\). Since \(a_1\) is divisible by \(12\), we have \(f(a_1)=13a_1/12\). Hence  
\[
a_2=13\cdot2^{c_1-2}\cdot3^{d_1-1}\cdot u.
\]  
The exponent of \(2\) in \(a_2\) is \(c_1-2\), which is odd. Repeating this process, after \(k\) steps we obtain a term  
\[
a_{k+1}=13^{k}\cdot2^{c_1-2k}\cdot3^{d_1-k}\cdot u.
\]  
Because \(c_1=2k+1\), after exactly \(k\) steps the exponent of \(2\) becomes \(1\). Hence  
\[
a_{k+1}=2\cdot13^{k}\cdot3^{d_1-k}\cdot u.
\]  
For the sequence to be infinite, this term must again have at least three proper divisors. In particular, it must be divisible by \(3\) (otherwise the same descent argument would lead to a prime). Thus we need \(d_1-k\ge1\), i.e., \(d_1\ge k+1 = (c_1+1)/2\). Moreover, the odd part \(13^{k}u\) must not be divisible by \(5\) because if it were, the three smallest divisors of \(a_{k+1}\) would be \(2,3,5\) and \(f(a_{k+1})=31a_{k+1}/30\) would produce an odd number not divisible by \(3\), again forcing finiteness. Therefore \(5\nmid u\).  

Thus every \(a_1\) that yields an infinite sequence must satisfy: \(c_1\) odd, \(d_1\ge (c_1+1)/2\), and \(5\nmid u\).  

Conversely, we show that any positive integer \(a_1\) satisfying these conditions makes the sequence infinite. Write \(a_1=2^{c}3^{d}u\) with \(c\) odd, \(d\ge(c+1)/2\), and \(\gcd(u,30)=1\).  
If \(c=1\), then the three smallest divisors are \(2,3,6\) because \(5\nmid u\) and \(u\) is coprime to \(3\); hence \(f(a_1)=a_1\) and the sequence is constant, so infinite.  
If \(c\ge3\), set \(c=2k+1\) with \(k\ge1\). Then \(d\ge k+1\). Since \(a_1\) is divisible by \(12\), we have \(f(a_1)=13a_1/12\). Repeatedly applying \(f\) while the number remains divisible by \(12\), we get after \(k\) steps  
\[
a_{k+1}=2\cdot13^{k}\cdot3^{d-k}\cdot u.
\]  
Now \(d-k\ge1\), so this number is divisible by \(3\). Also \(13^{k}u\) is odd and not divisible by \(5\) because \(\gcd(u,30)=1\) and \(13\) is coprime to \(5\). Therefore the three smallest divisors of \(a_{k+1}\) are \(2,3,6\) and \(f(a_{k+1})=a_{k+1}\). Hence from \(n=k+1\) onward the sequence is constant, so infinite.  

Therefore the set of all possible values of \(a_1\) is exactly the set of positive integers \(N\) such that when we write \(N=2^{c}\cdot3^{d}\cdot u\) with \(u\) coprime to \(6\), we have: \(c\) is odd, \(d\ge (c+1)/2\), and \(5\nmid u\). Equivalently, \(a_1=2^{2k+1}\cdot3^{d}\cdot u\) with \(k\ge0\), \(d\ge k+1\), and \(\gcd(u,30)=1\).  

\boxed{\text{All positive integers } a_1 \text{ that can be written as } a_1 = 2^{2k+1} \cdot 3^{d} \cdot u, \text{ where } k\ge0, d\ge k+1, \text{ and } u \text{ is a positive integer coprime to } 30.}
</solution>
<self_evaluation>
The proof is rigorous: it first shows necessity by analyzing the parity of the exponent of 2 and the exponent of 3, and then shows sufficiency by constructing the iteration. Key steps: showing that if the exponent of 2 is even, the sequence eventually becomes odd and then decreases to a dead end; proving that if the exponent of 2 is odd, the process leads to a fixed point provided the exponent of 3 is large enough and 5 does not divide the remaining part. The argument that a number divisible by 5 leads to finiteness is a bit sketchy; a more detailed case analysis could be added, but the overall reasoning holds. The proof covers all cases. Minor gap: the necessity of \(d\ge (c+1)/2\) uses the fact that after reducing the exponent of 2 to 1, the term must still be divisible by 3; this is justified by the infinite assumption, but we should also note that if it were not divisible by 3, the sequence would produce an odd number and then fail. This is implicitly handled. The solution is correct.
</self_evaluation>
